Subject:    <a href="?t=95837888800019&r=1&w=2">Re: Name server database pollution</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837784400012&r=1&w=2">Jeffrey I. Schiller &lt;jis () BITSY ! MIT ! EDU&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198704">1987-04-11 20:21:04</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926825&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837781926825&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

Has anyone thought of the idea of putting a little self protection into
name resolver implementations? For example how about not cacheing any
RR that claims to have a TTL greater then 1 year. This would eliminate
the bogus RRs floating around with 3 year TTLs. Another approach might
be to have a local idea of "Forever" which is min'd with the supplied
TTL of any incoming RR.

			-Jeff

